<paragraph blockId="18.[813,1419,856,915]" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">
<emphasis box="[813,1419,856,881]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="645" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,1028,856,881]" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">Habit and habitat.</emphasis>
Scattered under 
<taxonomicName box="[1218,1419,857,881]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Coccoloba" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="645" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uvifera">
<emphasis box="[1218,1419,857,881]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">Coccoloba uvifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
in coastal vegetation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[813,1420,932,1229]" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,932,956]" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">Identification.</emphasis>
This species can be recognized by the cream pileus that becomes lilac towards the margin, the white, fragile lamellae without lamellulae, the association with 
<taxonomicName box="[920,1127,1035,1059]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Coccoloba" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="645" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[920,1037,1035,1059]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">Coccoloba</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, and the verrucose, subreticulate, subglobose basidiospores of 6–8 × 5–6.5 µm. Our material agrees with the description provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pegler DN" box="[813,953,1137,1161]" pageId="18" pageNumber="645" refId="ref17566" refString="Pegler DN (1983) Agaric flora of the Lesser Antilles. Marston Book Services, London, 721 pp." type="book" year="1983">Pegler (1983)</bibRefCitation>
but presents paler basidiomata. 
<taxonomicName authority="Pegler" authorityName="Pegler" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Russulaceae" genus="Russula" kingdom="Fungi" order="Russulales" pageId="18" pageNumber="645" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="diversicolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="645">Russula diversicolor</emphasis>
Pegler
</taxonomicName>
is a tropical species but it differs in hav- ing a yellowish basidioma (
<bibRefCitation author="Pegler DN" box="[1106,1237,1205,1229]" pageId="18" pageNumber="645" refId="ref17566" refString="Pegler DN (1983) Agaric flora of the Lesser Antilles. Marston Book Services, London, 721 pp." type="book" year="1983">Pegler 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
